messages.content:
THOUGHT: The crash stems from GVNSink creating PHI nodes for operands that are InlineAsm values, which the verifier rejects as "taking the address of an inline asm." In sinkLastInstruction, when an operand differs across predecessors, the pass unconditionally creates a PHI. To fix this, I will add an early bail-out before PHI creation: if any operand that would require a PHI is an InlineAsm in any of the predecessor instructions, skip sinking this instruction entirely. I'll insert this guard just before the PHI creation comment.

```bash
sed -i '/// Create a new PHI in the successor block and populate it\./i\    
    // If creating a PHI would require putting an InlineAsm value into it,
    // that would effectively take the address of inline asm, which is invalid.
    // In such a case, bail out of sinking for this instruction.
    // This can happen when the operand is the callee of a call to inline asm,
    // which is represented as a pointer-typed InlineAsm value.
    bool HasInlineAsmOperand = isa<InlineAsm>(I0->getOperand(O)) ||
                               llvm::any_of(Insts, [O](const Instruction *I) {
                                 return isa<InlineAsm>(I->getOperand(O));
                               });
    if (HasInlineAsmOperand) {
      LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "GVNSink: skipping sinking due to InlineAsm operand "
                           "requiring PHI\n");
      return;
    }
' llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVNSink.cpp && submit-patch
```

